                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="12746346" author="stack" created="Fri, 21 Aug 2009 23:09:14 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Does stargate provide this Andrew?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12746569" author="apurtell" created="Sun, 23 Aug 2009 05:45:22 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Clients can set Content-Encoding to gzip or deflate and use the appropriate encoder and Jetty will just handle it. I expect other servlet containers will do the same.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Server side if Stargate is deployed as a WAR, the container usually has support for compression of dynamic content. For example, for Jetty: &lt;a href=&quot;http://docs.codehaus.org/display/JETTY/GZIP+Compression&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://docs.codehaus.org/display/JETTY/GZIP+Compression&lt;/a&gt; . The user would need to set up the GZIP filter using regular expressions matching on paths. I think this is appropriate. Not all tables/use cases want the overhead. I don&apos;t think a REST servlet should force it on. &lt;/p&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="12746650" author="stack" created="Sun, 23 Aug 2009 18:19:20 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;OK.   Marking as &apos;wont fix&apos; since its a feature containers provide.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
